# BlazeCode

BlazeCode is a lightweight, fast, terminal-based AI coding agent written in Python. It combines the simplicity of codex CLI's chat-style interface with the multi-provider flexibility of aider, in a single scrolling conversation that feels like chatting with a colleague rather than operating a full-screen TUI.

## Features

- Single scrolling terminal conversation (no full-screen TUI, no client/server)
- Multiple LLM providers through one interface: OpenAI, Anthropic, Gemini, Groq, Ollama, OpenRouter, and any OpenAI-compatible endpoint
- Agentic tool loop: read, write, edit files; list/glob and grep; run shell commands
- Approval workflow for any file write or shell command, with `--yolo` auto-approve mode
- Persistent session history stored as JSONL in `~/.blazecode/sessions/`
- Markdown rendering with syntax-highlighted code blocks and unified diffs
- Slash commands: `/help`, `/model`, `/clear`, `/exit`, `/yolo`

## Install (development)

```bash
git clone <this-repo> blazecode
cd blazecode
pip install -e .
```

This installs the `blazecode` command on your PATH.

## Quick start

```bash
export ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=sk-ant-...
blazecode
```

You will be dropped into a chat session. Type your request; BlazeCode will call tools, ask for approval before mutating anything, and stream the final answer.

For a single non-interactive turn (scripting use):

```bash
blazecode "fix the off-by-one error in main.py"
```

## Supported providers

| Shortcut | Provider   | Model string                            | Required env var      |
| -------- | ---------- | --------------------------------------- | --------------------- |
| `gpt`    | OpenAI     | `gpt-5`                                 | `OPENAI_API_KEY`      |
| `claude` | Anthropic  | `anthropic/claude-sonnet-4-6`           | `ANTHROPIC_API_KEY`   |
| `gemini` | Google     | `gemini/gemini-2.5-pro`                 | `GEMINI_API_KEY`      |
| `groq`   | Groq       | `groq/llama-3.3-70b-versatile`          | `GROQ_API_KEY`        |
| `ollama` | Ollama     | `ollama/llama3`                         | (no key, local server)|
| `openrouter` | OpenRouter | `openrouter/<model>`                 | `OPENROUTER_API_KEY`  |

Any litellm-format model string with a provider prefix also works directly, e.g. `blazecode -m openai/gpt-4o`.

Run `blazecode models` for the full table and examples.

## Configuration

Create `~/.blazecode/config.toml` for global defaults:

```toml
[default]
model = "claude"
permission = "ask"
max_iterations = 25

[providers.anthropic]
api_key = "sk-ant-..."
```

Project-local overrides go in `./.blazecode.toml` in the working directory.

API keys in TOML only set the environment variable if it is not already set in the real environment — real env vars always win.

## Slash commands

| Command       | Action                                |
| ------------- | ------------------------------------- |
| `/help`       | Show available commands and providers |
| `/model <n>`  | Switch model mid-session              |
| `/clear`      | Clear the visible conversation        |
| `/yolo`       | Toggle auto-approve for this session  |
| `/exit`       | Quit BlazeCode                        |

